# Module 4: Home Networks

## 4.1 Home Network Basics

### 4.1.2 Components of a Home Network
Devices that may connect to a home network (besides an integrated router):
- Desktop computers
- Gaming systems
- Smart TV systems
- Printers
- Scanners
- Security cameras
- Telephones
- Climate control devices

- As new technologies emerge, more household functions will rely on the network for connectivity and control.
- A typical home setup: ISP → Router → connects to Smart TV, Laptop, Smartphone, Gaming Console, Entertainment System (all part of the **Home Wireless Local Area Network / WLAN**).

### 4.1.3 Typical Home Network Routers
Home/small business routers typically have **two primary types of ports**:

| Port Type | Description |
|---|---|
| **Ethernet Ports** | Connect to the internal switch portion of the router; usually labeled "Ethernet" or "LAN." All devices connected here are on the **same local network**. |
| **Internet Port** | Connects the router to a *different* network (e.g., to a cable/DSL modem for internet access). |

- Many home routers also include a **radio antenna** and built-in **wireless access point**.
- By default, wireless devices are on the **same local network** as devices plugged into the LAN switch ports.
- The **internet port** is the only port on a different network by default.

### 4.1.4 Check Your Understanding – Answers
1. **False** – a home router does NOT only provide wired access; it typically includes wireless too.
2. **Ethernet port** – used to connect a wired device to the internal switch of the home router.

