## 4.2 Network Technologies in the Home

### 4.2.1 LAN Wireless Frequencies
- Most home network wireless tech uses the **unlicensed 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz** frequency bands.
- **Bluetooth** uses the 2.4 GHz band:
  - Low-speed, short-range communication.
  - Advantage: one-to-many communication (can talk to many devices at once).
  - Preferred for peripherals (wireless mice, keyboards, printers) and audio (speakers, headphones).
- **IEEE 802.11 (Wi-Fi)** also uses 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands:
  - Transmits at a much higher power level than Bluetooth → greater range and improved throughput.
- Certain areas of the electromagnetic spectrum can be used **without a permit**.
- Spectrum reference points:
  - Cordless phones: 902–928 MHz
  - IEEE 802.11 b/g/n/ad: 2.400–2.4835 GHz
  - IEEE 802.11 a/n/ac/ad: 5.725–5.850 GHz

### 4.2.2 Wired Network Technologies
- Some devices still benefit from a **wired switch connection** (not shared with other network users).
- Most common wired protocol: **Ethernet** — a suite of protocols for communication over a wired LAN.
- Directly connected devices typically use an **Ethernet patch cable** (usually unshielded twisted pair/UTP) with **RJ-45 connectors**.
- Newer homes may already have Ethernet wall jacks; homes without UTP wiring can use technologies like **powerline** for wired connectivity.

**Wired Technologies:**
| Technology | Description |
|---|---|
| **Category 5e Cable** | Most common LAN wiring; made of 4 twisted wire pairs to reduce electrical interference |
| **Coaxial Cable** | Inner wire surrounded by a tubular insulating layer, then a tubular conducting shield; usually has an external insulating sheath/jacket |
| **Fiber-Optic Cable** | Glass or plastic, about the diameter of a human hair; carries digital info at very high speeds over long distances; very high bandwidth |

### 4.2.3 Check Your Understanding – Answers
1. **True** – certain areas of the electromagnetic spectrum can be used without a permit.
2. **False** – Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, and cordless phones do NOT all use the same frequency ranges.
3. **Coaxial cable** – has an inner wire surrounded by a tubular insulating layer, then a tubular conducting shield.

