## 4.3 Wireless Standards

### 4.3.1 Wi-Fi Networks
- Wireless standards ensure devices can communicate — specifying RF spectrum used, data rates, transmission methods, etc.
- **IEEE (Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers)** — main organization creating wireless technical standards.
- **IEEE 802.11** standard governs the WLAN environment; amendments describe different wireless communication standards.
- Wireless LAN standards collectively = **Wi-Fi**, using 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz bands.
- **Wi-Fi Alliance** — tests wireless LAN devices from different manufacturers; the **Wi-Fi logo** on a device means it meets standards and should work with other same-standard devices.
- Standards constantly improve connectivity/speed — manufacturers implement new standards quickly.

### 4.3.2 Wireless Settings
Key wireless router settings:

| Setting | Description |
|---|---|
| **Network Mode** | Type of technology supported (802.11b, 802.11g, 802.11n, or Mixed Mode) |
| **Network Name (SSID)** | Identifies the WLAN; all devices in the WLAN must use the same SSID |
| **Standard Channel** | Channel used for communication; default = Auto (AP determines the optimum channel) |
| **SSID Broadcast** | Whether the SSID is broadcast to devices in range; default = Enabled |

- **Network Mode details:**
  - If all devices use the same 802.11 standard, maximum speed for that standard is achieved.
  - If the AP only accepts one standard, non-matching devices can't connect.
  - **Mixed mode**: supports devices using any existing Wi-Fi standard — useful for older devices.
- **SSID details:**
  - Case-sensitive, alphanumeric, up to **32 characters**.
  - Sent in the header of all frames transmitted over the WLAN.
  - Tells wireless stations (STAs) which WLAN they belong to and who they can communicate with.
  - Essentially the "name" of the network.
  - Routers broadcast SSID by default, letting clients auto-discover the network name.
  - If SSID broadcast is disabled, the SSID must be entered manually on devices.
  - Disabling SSID broadcast makes it harder for legit clients to find the network, but is **not sufficient** alone to stop unauthorized access — strong encryption should always be used.

### 4.3.3 Check Your Understanding – Answers
1. **Wi-Fi Alliance** – responsible for testing wireless LAN devices.
2. **The Service Set Identifier (SSID)** – used to identify a specific wireless network.
3. **False** – if devices use a variety of 802.11 standards, you should NOT set the network to the highest standard only (older devices wouldn't connect); use mixed/legacy mode instead.

