## 4.4 Set Up a Home Router

### 4.4.1 First Time Setup
- Many home wireless routers have an **automatic setup utility** for basic configuration — usually requires a PC/laptop connected via a **wired port**.
- If no wired device is available, configure wireless client software on a laptop/tablet first.
- **Wired connection steps:**
  - Plug an Ethernet patch cable into the computer's network port and into a **LAN port** on the router (NOT the port labeled "Internet").
  - The **Internet port** connects to the DSL or cable modem.
  - Some routers have a built-in modem — verify the connection type matches your internet service:
    - **Cable modem**: coaxial terminal, accepts a **BNC-type connector**.
    - **DSL**: port for telephone-type cable, usually an **RJ-11 connector**.
- After confirming connection (link lights active), the computer needs an **IP address** — usually assigned automatically via a **DHCP server** on the router.
- If no IP address is received, manually configure IP address, subnet mask, default gateway, and DNS (check router documentation).

### 4.4.2 Design Considerations
Before configuring the router, consider:

**What should my network be called?**
- If SSID broadcasting is on, all wireless clients in range can see the SSID name.
- Avoid including the device model/brand name in the SSID — default settings and known security weaknesses for specific models are easy to find online.

**What types of devices will attach to my network?**
- Wireless devices have radios that work within a specific frequency range/standard.
- A device supporting only 802.11 b/g won't connect if the router is set to accept only 802.11n or 802.11ac.
- If all devices support the same standard, the network runs at optimum speed.
- For devices that don't support n/ac, enable **legacy mode** (aka **mixed mode**, depending on router) — can include a combination of 802.11a/b/g/n/ac for easy access by legacy devices.

**How do I add new devices?**
- Access decisions should be based on how you plan to use the network.
- Some routers support **guest access** — a special SSID coverage area allowing open access but restricted to internet use only.

